feature.name: Scenario outlines
feature.description:
Copying and pasting scenarios to use different values quickly
  becomes tedious and repetitive. Scenario outlines allow us to more
  concisely express these examples through the use of a template with
  placeholders, using Scenario Outline, Examples with tables and < >
  delimited parameters.

  The Scenario Outline steps provide a template which is never directly
  run. A Scenario Outline is run once for each row in the Examples section
  beneath it (not counting the first row).

  The way this works is via placeholders. Placeholders must be contained
  within < > in the Scenario Outline's steps - see the examples below.

  **IMPORTANT:** Your step definitions will never have to match a
  placeholder. They will need to match the values that will replace the
  placeholder.

  You can also write descriptions attached to individual scenarios - see
  the examples below for how this can be used.

  It's possible to have your descriptions run over more than one line,
  and you can have blank lines too. As long as you don't start a line
  with a Given, When, Then, Background:, Scenario: or similar, you're
  fine: otherwise Gherkin will start to pay attention.

feature.name: Using star notation instead of Given/When/Then
feature.description:
Cucumber supports the star notation when writing features: instead of
  using Given/When/Then, you can simply use a star rather like you would
  use a bullet point.

  message showing you the code snippet you need to use to implement the
  step.

feature.name: Parameter Types
feature.description:
Parameter Types allow you to convert primitive string arguments captured in step definitions
  into more meaningful data types.

background.description:
Let's just create a simple feature for testing out parameter types.
    We also have a Person class that we need to be able to build.

docString.content:
Feature:
  Scenario:
    Given Joe has gone home
    When Sally contacts Joe

# It works with Regular Expressions
Given /([A-Z]\w+) has gone home/ do |person|
  expect(person.name).to eq 'Joe'
end

# It works with Cucumber Expressions too
When "{person} contacts {person}" do |contacter, contactee|
  expect(contacter.name).to eq 'Sally'
  expect(contactee.name).to eq 'Joe'
end

scenario.name: Parameter type defined with ParameterType method
scenario.description: This is the most basic way to use a parameter type.

docString.content:
ParameterType(
  name: 'person',
  regexp: /[A-Z]\w+/,
  transformer: -> (name) { make_person(name) },
  use_for_snippets: false
)

module MyWorld
  def make_person(name)
    Person.new(name)
  end
end
World(MyWorld)

scenario.name: Parameter type with group nested in optional group

docString.content:
ParameterType(
  name: "Employer",
  regexp: /Employer(?: "([^"]*)")?/,
  transformer: -> (name = nil) do
    name || 'Unnamed'
  end
)

ParameterType(
  name: 'person',
  regexp: /[A-Z]\w+/,
  transformer: -> (name) { Person.new(name) }
)

    Then the name should be "Unnamed"

Given "the {Employer}" do |name|
  @name = name
end

Given "the name should be {string}" do |name|

end

feature.name: World
feature.description:
In order to isolate each test scenario, the steps definitions belonging to the
  same scenario will run in a isolated context, called 'world'. A world also
  contains the helpers methods that will be used in the step definitions.

  It is possible to add helpers methods to a world in three different ways:

  1. Passing a module. In this case its methods will be added directly to the
     world and be usable in the step definitions.

  2. Passing a block, where the return value is the world object.

  3. Passing a hash, where the keys are namespaces and the values are
     modules. In this case, the methods of each module will be accessible using
     the key as prefix.

scenario.name: A world is extended using a module

docString.content:
module Helpers
  def helper_method
    42
  end
end

World(Helpers)

Then /^the helper method is called$/ do
  expect(helper_method).to eql(42)
end

Feature: Calling a method
  Scenario: I call a method without namespaces
    Then the helper method is called

scenario.name: A world is created using a block

docString.content:
class Helper
  def helper_method
    42
  end
end

World do
  Helper.new
end

Then /^the helper method is called$/ do
  expect(helper_method).to eql(42)
end

Feature: Calling a method
  Scenario: I call a method from a namespace
    Then the helper method is called

scenario.name: A world is extended using a module with namespace

docString.content:
module Helpers
  def helper_method
    42
  end
end

World(my_namespace: Helpers)

Then /^the helper method is called$/ do
  expect(my_namespace.helper_method).to eql(42)
end

    Then the helper method is called

  end
end

module ModuleTwo

    42
  end
end

World(module_one: ModuleOne, module_two: ModuleTwo)

Then /^the helper method is called$/ do
  expect(module_one.forty_one).to eql(41)
  expect(module_two.forty_two).to eql(42)
end
